Australian Bird Baths

Author

Vinny Chloros

Abstract

This bird bath data from Cleary et al, 2016 is a collaborative effort between researchers and citizen scientists to track activity in bird baths throughout Australia. Because of the arid conditions in most of the region, bird baths might prove to be a vital resource for birds who rely on them as a water source.

Introduction

The Bathing Birds Study was conceptualized by researchers at Deakin University and Griffith University, aiming to identify the usage of bird baths by birds in different situations. Data was collected over two four-week periods: one in 2014 in winter, and the other in 2015 in summer.

Code 
tuesdata <- tidytuesdayR::tt_load('2021-08-31')

bird_baths <- tuesdata$bird_baths
Code 
library(tidymodels)

birds_splits <- initial_split(bird_baths, prop = 0.5)

exploratory_data <- training(birds_splits)
test_data <- testing(birds_splits)

Question(s)

  1. Does bird bath usage vary by season and/or region?

  2. Is there a bias for spotting in urban regions since more birders are looking?

  3. How does climate factor into bird bath usage?

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Understanding Data Format

As a first step, letâ€™s take a quick peek into the data to see what our values look like at a glance.

Code 
library(kableExtra)

exploratory_data$survey_year <- as.character(exploratory_data$survey_year)

  kbl() |>

I realized that this table wasnâ€™t actually giving me the number of birds seen in these regions, but instead just the number of instances that birds were found. Within bird_count, the actual number of birds seen could vary from 0 to >100.

Here, I figured out how the data was actually sorted within the data frame: there is an instance for each possible bird species within the overarching habitats and dates. To find what Iâ€™m actually interested in, Iâ€™ll have to summarize the number of birds observed within each specific instance (bioregion + urban/rural + year).

Code 
exploratory_data |>
  filter(bird_count > 0) |>
  group_by(survey_year) |>
  summarize(
    sum_bird_count <- sum(bird_count, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) |>
  kbl() |>
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped")
survey_year sum_bird_count <- sum(bird_count, na.rm = TRUE)
2014 1466
2015 1341
NA 2568

Starting Plots, Single Variable by Count

Now, back to the investigation, Iâ€™ll try to see if I can summarize the total birds spotted by the region of they were spotted in.

Code 
exploratory_data |>
  filter(!is.na(bioregions)) |>
  filter(bird_count > 0) |>
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = bird_count, y = bioregions, fill = bioregions)) +
  labs(title = "Bird Count by Bioregion",
       x = "Number of Birds",
       y = "Region") +
  scale_fill_discrete() +
  guides(fill = "none")

Code 
exploratory_data |>
  filter(bird_count > 0) |>
  filter(!is.na(bioregions)) |>
  group_by(bioregions) |>
  summarize(
    sum_bird_count <- sum(bird_count, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) |>
  kbl() |>
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped") |>
  scroll_box(height = "300px")

Success! From this graph, we can see that the largest amount of birds were seen in the Sydney Basin, which makes up around 37% of all the observations. In comparison, South Eastern Queensland (SE Queensland) has the next largest amount of sightings with just over half the amount of birds (~22% of the data). Brigalow Belt South and Victorian Volcano Plain were almost tied for the least amount of birds, only differing by 2 sightings (both around 2%).

Further Analysis, Multiple Variables Against Count

Code 
exploratory_data |>
  filter(!is.na(bioregions)) |>
  filter(!is.na(survey_year)) |>
  filter(bird_count > 0) |>
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = bird_count, y = bioregions, fill = bioregions)) +
  labs(title = "Bird Count by Bioregion and Year",
       x = "Number of Birds",
       y = "Region") +
  facet_grid(. ~ survey_year) +
  scale_fill_discrete() +
  guides(fill = "none")

Code 
exploratory_data |>

  filter(!is.na(bioregions)) |>
  filter(bird_count > 0) |>
  ggplot() +

  labs(title = "Bird Count by Bioregion and Urbanness",
       x = "Number of Birds",
       y = "Region") +
  facet_grid(. ~ urban_rural) +
  scale_fill_discrete() +
  guides(fill = "none")
